# The Robot Economy's Missing Answer

*Eight leaders, twenty-four questions, zero detailed answers—yet*

**By Julian — February 2026**

---

> *"The factory of the future will have only two employees: a man and a dog. The man will be there to feed the dog. The dog will be there to keep the man from touching the equipment."*
> — Warren Bennis

---

## The Catch-22 Nobody Is Solving

Here is the simplest version of the problem. In our current economy, money moves in a circle: companies pay humans wages to produce goods, humans use those wages to buy the goods, and companies use that revenue to pay wages again. Every serious AI company on earth is working to remove the first step—wages—from this loop. Not partially. Completely. The explicit goal is artificial general intelligence and physical automation sophisticated enough to perform virtually all economically productive labor.

If you succeed, the second step—consumption—becomes impossible for most people. The third step—revenue—collapses. Your robot armies stand idle in warehouses full of goods that nobody can afford to buy. This is not a novel observation. Economists have been writing about it for decades. What is novel is the timeline. We are no longer debating whether this transition will happen. The people building these systems say it will happen within ten to twenty years. Some say sooner.

And yet, when you press the leaders of the frontier AI companies—the people whose work will trigger this disruption—for specifics on how the economic transition will actually work, you get remarkably thin answers. You get "universal basic income" offered as a phrase, not a plan. You get vague gestures toward "abundance." You get philosophical optimism untethered from mechanism.

This article is an attempt to move past the hand-waving. It lays out the real mechanics of the problem, stress-tests the proposed solutions, and then asks direct questions of the people who have the most influence over how this unfolds.

---

## I. The Circular Flow Problem Is Real—But the Accounting Version Is Solvable

The most common version of the concern goes like this: if UBI is funded by taxing companies, and companies get their revenue from people spending UBI, then it's just money going in a circle. Where does the wealth actually come from?

This version of the problem is actually solvable, and the solution is important to understand before we get to the harder issues. Economies have always been circular. You work for a company, they give you money, you give it back to them to buy food. The mechanism is a loop by design. What changes in an automated economy is not the loop itself—it's the reason you receive the money. Today you receive it in exchange for labor. In the future, the proposal is that you receive it in exchange for citizenship.

Moreover, sovereign currency issuers—governments that issue and control their own fiat currency—are not operationally constrained the way households are. The government does not need to collect taxes before it can spend. It credits accounts first and collects taxes later. This is not a heterodox claim; it is a description of how the Federal Reserve and Treasury actually operate. Taxes serve to create demand for the currency, manage inflation, and shape distribution—not to "fund" spending in the way that your checking account funds your grocery bill.

So the accounting version of the problem—where does the initial money come from?—has an answer. The constraint on government spending is not revenue. It is inflation and real resource availability. Which leads us to the problems that are genuinely hard.

---

## II. The Hard Problems: Scarcity, Power, and the Transition

The deflation promise has limits. The optimistic case says that when robots handle agriculture, construction, manufacturing, and transport, the cost of goods crashes toward the cost of raw materials plus energy. A house costs almost nothing to build. Food costs pennies. In that world, even a modest UBI buys a comfortable life.

This is plausible for manufactured goods. It is not plausible for the things that actually consume most household budgets. Land in desirable locations is fixed-supply. A robot can build a house cheaply, but the lot in Austin or Bend or Brooklyn still costs what the market will bear. If anything, wealth concentration from automation could increase real estate prices in desirable areas as capital owners bid up scarce positional goods. Healthcare costs are driven as much by regulatory capture, administrative overhead, and the inherent complexity of human biology as by labor costs. Energy, which powers the entire automated economy, faces its own massive supply constraints.

The economy likely bifurcates into an "automated sector" where prices fall dramatically and a "scarce sector"—housing, energy, healthcare, land, status goods, human-performed services—where prices remain high or increase. Your standard of living in this world depends entirely on the ratio of your spending in each sector.

The tax base may evaporate. Most UBI proposals assume fat corporate profits available to be taxed. But if automation drives marginal costs toward zero and competition forces prices down, then revenues shrink, profits compress, and the "automation profits tax" yields far less than projected—unless monopoly power persists. The sustainable tax base likely shifts away from profits entirely and toward taxing scarce inputs and rents: land value, resource extraction royalties, energy and carbon, spectrum and compute licensing, and excess profits from monopoly positions.

The ownership question is more important than the tax question. The most stable solution to funding a post-labor economy is not a perpetual political fight over tax rates. It is changing who owns the automated capital. A sovereign wealth fund that holds broad equity in the companies benefiting from publicly funded AI research—and nearly all of them benefit from publicly funded research—converts UBI from a redistributive transfer into a dividend on public investment. Alaska's Permanent Fund and Norway's Government Pension Fund provide working models. The question is whether this ownership stake gets established during the transition, when the leverage still exists, or after the concentration is irreversible, when it doesn't.

---

## III. The Embodiment Pipeline: How Intelligence Gets a Body

The public conversation about AI and jobs focuses almost exclusively on software—chatbots replacing customer service, AI writing marketing copy, algorithms reading medical scans. This misses the far more consequential development already underway: the systematic effort to give AI systems physical bodies capable of performing manual labor. The embodiment pipeline is not speculative. It is funded, it has timelines, and the major players have made their strategies explicit. As of early 2026, between 13,000 and 18,000 humanoid robots were sold globally in 2025 alone. The industry has crossed from research prototypes into commercial reality.

Understanding the pipeline requires seeing it as a supply chain with distinct layers, each controlled by different companies, all converging on the same endpoint: autonomous physical labor at scale.

### The Hardware Layer

On January 21, 2026, Tesla officially commenced mass production of Optimus Gen 3 at its Fremont factory, converting its Model S and Model X production lines to robot manufacturing. Tesla's target price remains below $30,000 per unit, with a long-term goal of $20,000 at million-unit volumes. Over 1,000 Optimus robots are already operating inside Tesla's own factories performing tasks like battery cell sorting. Musk has stated the Gen 3 production line will target one million units annually by late 2026—though independent assessments suggest actual 2025 production was in the hundreds, not thousands. Figure AI, now valued at $39 billion after a $1 billion Series C in September 2025—a 15x increase from its $2.6 billion valuation just eighteen months earlier—launched its third-generation humanoid, Figure 03, in October 2025. Its dedicated BotQ manufacturing facility in Austin is operational with 12,000-unit annual capacity, targeting 100,000 robots over four years with paying customers including BMW and reportedly UPS. Apptronik's Apollo humanoid has a partnership with Mercedes-Benz for automotive assembly. Agility Robotics' Digit is operating in Amazon warehouses. 1X Technologies, backed by OpenAI, opened consumer preorders for its NEO home robot in October 2025 with a 2026 delivery window. Boston Dynamics unveiled its all-new Electric Atlas at CES 2026, with initial fleets shipping to Hyundai and Google DeepMind. This is not a single company's moonshot. It is an industry forming in real time, with billions in committed capital.

### The China Factor in Hardware

The most striking development in the hardware layer is happening in China. Chinese companies now control roughly 90% of the humanoid robot market by unit volume. Unitree Robotics shipped over 5,500 humanoid robots in 2025—more than Tesla, Figure AI, and Agility Robotics combined (each shipped approximately 150). Shanghai-based Agibot sold 5,168 units. Unitree's R1 humanoid, launched in July 2025, starts at $5,900—a price point the industry thought was years away. Chinese EV giants are pivoting aggressively: BYD is building an embodied intelligence lab and aims to deploy 1,500 humanoids in 2025, scaling to 20,000 by 2026. GAC Group, XPeng, Nio, and Geely all have active humanoid programs. China registered 5,688 humanoid robotics patents from 2020 to 2025, nearly four times the U.S. total. Morgan Stanley's assessment: "Adoption should be relatively slow until the mid-2030s, accelerating in the late 2030s and 2040s." But China's deployment velocity suggests that timeline may compress significantly.

### The Intelligence Layer

The intelligence layer has undergone a revolution in the past twelve months. Google DeepMind launched Gemini Robotics in March 2025—a full vision-language-action model built on Gemini 2.0 that directly converts visual information and natural language instructions into physical robot motor commands. DeepMind followed with Gemini Robotics On-Device in June 2025, an on-device model that runs locally on robots without network connectivity, and then Gemini Robotics 1.5 in September 2025, which adds agentic reasoning—the robot can now plan multi-step tasks, search the internet for information it needs, and explain its reasoning in natural language while acting. These models are already available to trusted partners including Agility Robotics, Boston Dynamics, and Apptronik, and the Gemini Robotics-ER 1.5 model is available to developers via the Gemini API. MIT Technology Review called it "one of the first announcements of people applying generative AI and large language models to advanced robots." DeepMind has also implemented constitutional AI safety mechanisms for robot behavior based on a generalization of Asimov's laws.

In a significant strategic shift, Figure AI exited its collaboration with OpenAI in February 2025, with CEO Brett Adcock citing a "major breakthrough" in end-to-end robot AI built entirely in-house. The resulting system, Helix, is a proprietary vision-language-action neural network using a "System 1 / System 2" architecture: System 2 handles high-level planning at 7-9 Hz while System 1 provides low-level motor control at 200 Hz. Adcock's reasoning was blunt: "We found that to solve embodied AI at scale in the real world, you have to vertically integrate robot AI. We can't outsource AI for the same reason we can't outsource our hardware." OpenAI, meanwhile, has rebuilt its robotics team, hired Caitlin Kalinowski (formerly head of Meta's AR glasses) to lead hardware efforts, filed trademark applications referencing humanoid robots, and continues backing 1X Technologies. Physical Intelligence raised $400 million in late 2024 to build a hardware-agnostic foundation model for robot control. Skild AI raised $300 million for a similar approach. Nvidia's GR00T foundation model and Isaac simulation platform continue to serve as the infrastructure layer connecting intelligence to hardware across the industry.

### The Musk Ecosystem Convergence

The most significant strategic development may be the Musk ecosystem convergence. xAI, Musk's AI company, was acquired by SpaceX in early 2026, and its Grok models are explicitly being developed to power Tesla's Optimus. Bloomberg reported that xAI spent $7.8 billion in the first nine months of 2025, with executives stating that the technology is "meant to power Tesla's Optimus robot, which is supposed to replace human labor." Musk described the strategy in a November 2025 interview: "Others are confined to the digital world, while we start from the physical world, incorporating the element of movement, which no one can match." This represents the most vertically integrated intelligence-to-embodiment pipeline in the industry: xAI builds the reasoning models, Tesla builds the robot hardware and the inference chips (the A15, targeting 2-3x Nvidia performance at 1/10 the cost), and SpaceX provides the manufacturing and deployment infrastructure. Whether Musk's companies can execute on this vision is an open question. What is not in question is that no other entity controls this much of the stack.

### Meta Enters the Race

Meta formally entered the embodied AI race in May 2025, when CTO Andrew Bosworth's internal memo revealed a new division within Reality Labs dedicated to developing "consumer humanoid robots" powered by Meta's Llama AI models. Meta has begun discussions with Unitree Robotics and Figure AI for hardware partnerships, though it does not plan to launch its own branded robot immediately. Meta's $65 billion AI infrastructure investment in 2025 includes robotics and its FAIR research lab has active robotics programs. The open-source dimension of Meta's strategy is particularly significant: Llama models that can be paired with commercially available robot hardware create conditions for rapid, decentralized deployment that is far harder to regulate than proprietary systems.

### The Convergence

The convergence of these layers is accelerating faster than most policy analysts anticipated. Goldman Sachs projects the humanoid robot market reaching $38 billion by 2035 and potentially $5 trillion by 2050. Manufacturing costs declined 40% year-over-year in 2024-2025, far exceeding earlier projections of 15-20% annual declines. The question is not whether embodied AI arrives but how quickly it scales from pilot programs to mass deployment—and whether any economic policy framework will be in place when it does.

---

## IV. The Timeline Is Not What You Think

Most public discussion of AI and economic disruption oscillates between two endpoints: "everything is fine, we've always adapted" and "robots take all the jobs." Neither is useful, because neither describes the transition period that the next ten to twenty years will actually be.

**2025–2032: The wage compression phase.** AI does not eliminate jobs wholesale in this period. It fragments them. A law firm needs one paralegal instead of four. A radiology department supervises AI reading ten times more scans with the same staff. A marketing team of twelve becomes a team of three with AI tools. Net employment may not crash, but wage pressure becomes severe in knowledge work for the first time in modern history. Simultaneously, the first wave of humanoid robots enters controlled environments—warehouses, factories, structured logistics. By early 2026, over 1,000 Optimus robots operate inside Tesla's factories. Figure AI's BotQ facility is producing units for BMW and a second major U.S. customer. Chinese manufacturers shipped an estimated 13,000–18,000 humanoid units globally in 2025, with Unitree alone accounting for 5,500. The political significance of this phase is enormous: it is the first time automation directly threatens both the blue-collar labor force and the college-educated professional class simultaneously.

**2032–2040: Physical automation reaches general deployment.** Humanoid robotics and autonomous vehicles have proven their reliability across millions of hours of commercial operation. The deployment expands from structured environments into semi-structured and unstructured ones—retail, food service, construction, agriculture, last-mile delivery. The economics become self-reinforcing: each generation of robots trains the next generation's AI models through operational data, while simulation environments compress the training cycle. Google DeepMind's Gemini Robotics models already allow robots to learn new tasks from as few as 50 to 100 demonstrations. By this point, structural unemployment is difficult to disguise through gig work and statistical reclassification.

**The energy bottleneck.** The entire automated economy runs on electricity. The United States currently generates roughly 4,000 terawatt-hours annually. Conservative projections for AI compute demand alone suggest the need to double or triple total generation capacity by 2035–2040, before adding autonomous vehicle fleets, robotic manufacturing, and automated agriculture. Permitting a single nuclear plant in the U.S. takes ten to fifteen years. Solar and wind face transmission constraints. The energy infrastructure buildout required for full automation is on the scale of the post-World War II industrial expansion, and we currently have neither the regulatory framework nor the political consensus to execute it at that speed.

**The robotics scaling curve.** There is a specific inflection point in the deployment of physical automation that deserves attention, and the data suggests it is arriving faster than expected. Manufacturing costs for humanoid robots declined 40% year-over-year in 2024-2025—far exceeding Goldman Sachs' earlier projections of 15-20% annual declines. Chinese manufacturer Unitree launched its R1 humanoid at $5,900 in July 2025, a price point the industry consensus said was years away. Tesla targets sub-$30,000 unit costs at scale, with $20,000 at million-unit volumes. At a $20,000 price point, a humanoid robot that works 24 hours a day, seven days a week, with no benefits, no workers' compensation, and no labor disputes, pays for itself in weeks at current minimum wage rates. The transition from "interesting pilot program" to "why would we ever hire a human for this" happens not gradually but as a step function once the price-performance threshold is crossed. China's coordinated industrial policy and aggressive cost reduction suggest that threshold may arrive on the Chinese manufacturing timeline rather than the American one.

**The China factor changes everything.** China recorded over 610 robotics investment deals in the first nine months of 2025, totaling $7 billion—a 250% increase year-over-year. China controls 63% of key companies in the global humanoid robot component supply chain. More than ten Chinese auto giants—including BYD, XPeng, Geely, GAC Group, and Nio—have active humanoid robot programs, leveraging their existing manufacturing expertise, supply chains, and factory floor experience. China's Ministry of Industry and Information Technology has issued guidelines targeting a full humanoid robot innovation system by 2025 and deep integration into the real economy by 2027. This is the EV playbook applied to robotics: state support, dozens of new entrants, rapid scaling, and cost leadership. The geopolitical dimension compounds the economic disruption question: even if the United States chose to slow deployment, China's pace would continue.

---

## V. The Darkest Scenario Is Already Partially True

The scenario that should concern us most is not mass unemployment. It is the possibility that the owners of automated systems no longer need a mass consumer base. If a sufficiently wealthy individual or corporation controls a robot fleet that can build homes, grow food, generate energy, and provide security, they do not need your purchasing power. The current economy runs on a mutual dependency: the wealthy need us to buy their products so they can stay wealthy. Automation could sever that dependency.

This is not a distant hypothetical. The decoupling of wealth generated from humans required is already well underway. Instagram had thirteen employees when it was acquired for one billion dollars. WhatsApp had fifty-five employees serving 450 million users. The trajectory is clear: increasingly vast economic value generated by increasingly few people, with increasingly little need for mass labor or mass consumption to sustain it.

The embodiment of AI accelerates this decoupling into the physical world. When the same dynamic that allowed thirteen people to create a billion-dollar software company extends to manufacturing, agriculture, logistics, and construction, the implications are qualitatively different. Software displacement left physical production intact—someone still had to make, move, and serve the physical goods. Robotic displacement removes that remaining dependency.

In the extreme version of this scenario, a small elite with automated production capacity becomes functionally self-sufficient. They do not need the tax base's purchasing power, do not need its labor, and—if autonomous security systems are sufficiently advanced—do not need its political consent. This is not inevitable, but it is a plausible equilibrium if capital concentration continues unchecked through the transition period.

---

## VI. The Two Strongest Objections—and Why They Don't Resolve the Problem

Any honest assessment of this transition must engage with the two most credible counter-arguments. These are not straw men. They are the arguments that thoughtful defenders of rapid deployment would actually make—and in private, do make. Both contain real substance. Neither resolves the core problem.

### Objection 1: The Geopolitical Prisoner's Dilemma

The argument goes like this: even if the United States wanted to slow the deployment of embodied AI to allow for economic adaptation, China will not. China recorded 610 robotics investment deals in the first nine months of 2025. Unitree shipped thirty-five times more humanoid units than Tesla. BYD is targeting 20,000 units by 2026. The Chinese government has issued explicit industrial policy targeting a full humanoid robot ecosystem by 2027. In this framing, any call to modulate deployment speed is strategic suicide—the equivalent of asking American steelmakers to slow production while Japan industrialized in the 1960s, except the stakes are existential rather than commercial.

This objection is real. It is also, conveniently, the objection that forecloses the entire policy discussion that these companies do not want to have. The Prisoner's Dilemma framing treats the pace of deployment as an exogenous variable—something that happens to us—rather than as a choice made by specific companies with specific financial incentives. It deserves scrutiny on three counts. First, the framing assumes that the only possible response to China's pace is matching it domestically with zero policy friction, when in fact the United States maintained a robust industrial base throughout the Cold War while simultaneously operating extensive labor protections, social insurance, and regulatory frameworks. Speed and governance are not mutually exclusive; the assertion that they are is a lobbying position, not an engineering constraint. Second, the companies making this argument are the same companies lobbying against the governance frameworks that would allow society to adapt at the speed they are moving. You cannot simultaneously argue that speed is non-negotiable because of geopolitical competition and then oppose the tax structures, ownership stakes, and transition programs that would make that speed survivable. Third, China itself is building its humanoid robot industry with extensive state coordination, industrial policy, and deployment guidelines. The implicit claim that the Chinese approach is "ungoverned speed" is inaccurate. It is differently governed speed—with the state playing a far more active role in directing where, how, and under what conditions robots are deployed.

The honest version of the geopolitical argument is not "we cannot slow down." It is "we need to build institutions that function at the speed we are moving." That is a fundamentally different project than the one currently underway, which is moving at maximum speed while building nothing.

### Objection 2: The Robot Savior Narrative (Demographic Collapse)

Most developed nations face severe workforce contraction due to aging populations and declining birth rates. Japan's working-age population has shrunk by over 13 million since its peak. South Korea's fertility rate is below 0.8. Germany, Italy, and increasingly China itself face the same trajectory. In this framing, humanoid robots arrive not as destroyers of jobs but as the solution to a labor crisis that would otherwise collapse pension systems, healthcare, and economic output. The robots do the work that there are not enough young humans to perform. This is the most intellectually honest version of the optimist case, and it has real data behind it.

But the demographic argument contains a critical timing mismatch that its proponents rarely address. Demographic decline is a slow-moving variable. It unfolds over decades as birth rate changes propagate through the age distribution. Automation deployment, as we have established, is a step function that accelerates dramatically once the price-performance threshold is crossed. These two curves do not arrive in a neat sequence where labor shortage peaks just as robots become capable. They overlap—creating a period, potentially lasting a decade or more, where both pressures operate simultaneously.

Consider the mechanics. Demographic decline does not affect all sectors equally. It hits healthcare, elder care, agriculture, and skilled trades hardest—sectors that are among the last to be automated due to the complexity of the work and the regulatory requirements. Meanwhile, automation hits manufacturing, logistics, warehousing, retail, and food service first—sectors that still employ tens of millions of workers who are not aging out of the workforce. The result is not a clean substitution but a mismatch: robots displacing workers in sectors where humans are still available, while labor shortages persist in sectors where robots are not yet capable. A 55-year-old warehouse worker displaced by a Figure 03 does not become an elder care nurse. The demographic argument treats "labor" as a fungible commodity. It is not.

Furthermore, the demographic case assumes that the economic transition mechanisms—how displaced workers receive income, how consumption is sustained, how the benefits of automation are distributed—are already solved. They are not. A world where robots fill demographic gaps and displaced workers receive adequate support is a world where the policy questions this article raises have been answered. Using the demographic case to argue that those questions do not need to be answered is circular reasoning.

Both objections contain truths that this article takes seriously. Geopolitical competition is real. Demographic decline is real. Neither eliminates the need for specific, mechanistic answers about how the economic transition works. If anything, they make the need more urgent—because they mean the deployment will happen faster and with fewer natural brakes than a purely domestic, purely economic analysis would suggest.

---

## VII. Questions for the Architects

The following questions are directed at the individuals and companies who have the most influence over how this transition unfolds. They are not rhetorical. They are requests for specifics—for mechanisms, timelines, and commitments—in areas where the public discussion has remained frustratingly vague.

---

### To Elon Musk — Tesla / Optimus, xAI, SpaceX

**Q1.** SpaceX's acquisition of xAI and the explicit strategy to use Grok models to power Optimus creates the most vertically integrated intelligence-to-embodiment pipeline in the industry. xAI spent $7.8 billion in the first nine months of 2025 building the AI brain for a robot body. Tesla builds the hardware and custom inference chips. SpaceX provides manufacturing infrastructure. You control the entire stack from reasoning to physical action. No entity in history has controlled this much of the chain from intelligence to physical labor. What governance framework do you believe should apply to a conglomerate in that position? Do you support any form of public oversight, ownership stake, or structural separation?

**Q2.** Tesla commenced mass production of Optimus Gen 3 on January 21, 2026, converting Model S and X lines to robot manufacturing at Fremont. You have stated targets of one million units annually by late 2026 and a $25 trillion Tesla valuation driven by robotics. Yet actual 2025 production was in the hundreds, not thousands. Independent assessments note that 10-million-unit-scale manufacturing of humanoid robots is genuinely unprecedented. Meanwhile, Chinese competitors shipped over 13,000 humanoid robots in 2025, with Unitree alone outselling Tesla by a factor of roughly 35:1. You yourself acknowledged at Davos 2026 that China will be the toughest competition. At what annual production volume does Tesla's own modeling suggest systemic labor displacement begins, and has Tesla modeled the macroeconomic feedback effects of deploying millions of units at the target $20,000 price?

**Q3.** You have described a future where "there will be no shortage of goods and services." But housing costs are driven by land scarcity, not construction costs. Energy infrastructure cannot be scaled on the timeline your own deployment projections require. What is your specific answer to the scarce-sector inflation problem—the reality that even with cheap manufactured goods, the things that matter most to household budgets remain supply-constrained?

---

### To Jensen Huang — Nvidia

**Q1.** Nvidia occupies a uniquely powerful position in the embodied AI pipeline. You provide the GPUs that train robot foundation models, the Omniverse platform where robots learn in simulation, the Isaac robotics platform, the GR00T humanoid foundation model, and the edge computing hardware that runs inference on deployed robots. You are simultaneously the supplier to every layer of the stack. What is Nvidia's assessment of the timeline for humanoid robots reaching commercial viability at scale, and at what point does Nvidia's own internal modeling suggest this triggers significant labor displacement?

**Q2.** Nvidia's simulation platforms collapse the training timeline for robotic systems from years to days. This is an extraordinary accelerant. Has Nvidia considered that by dramatically compressing the development cycle for physical automation, it is also compressing the window for economic and political adaptation? Does Nvidia have any position on whether the pace of this acceleration should be modulated, or is maximum speed the default assumption?

**Q3.** If humanoid robots become the dominant form of physical labor, Nvidia's hardware and platforms become critical infrastructure for the global economy in a way that exceeds even its current role in AI compute. What governance framework does Nvidia believe should apply to a company in that position? Should Nvidia's robotics platform be treated as a public utility?

---

### To Demis Hassabis — Google DeepMind

**Q1.** Gemini Robotics represents the most advanced vision-language-action model available for physical robot control. In twelve months, DeepMind went from the initial March 2025 launch to Gemini Robotics 1.5 in September 2025, which adds agentic reasoning—robots that plan multi-step tasks, search the internet for information, and explain their reasoning while acting. The model is already available to partners including Boston Dynamics, Agility Robotics, and Apptronik, and the on-device variant requires as few as 50 to 100 demonstrations to learn new tasks. This is the bridge technology that converts hardware platforms into genuinely capable autonomous workers. What is DeepMind's internal timeline for when these models reach the reliability threshold for unsupervised commercial deployment, and has DeepMind modeled the economic displacement implications of that milestone?

**Q2.** Google's core business model depends on a mass consumer internet—billions of people with enough purchasing power to be valuable to advertisers. Embodied AI deployed at scale collapses the need for human labor and therefore mass purchasing power. Gemini Robotics is now powering the robots being deployed by companies that will directly displace workers. Has DeepMind or Alphabet modeled the economic conditions required to sustain its own business in a world where its robotics AI technology succeeds? At what point does automation-driven demand destruction threaten the advertising model that funds DeepMind's research?

**Q3.** DeepMind has implemented constitutional AI safety mechanisms for Gemini Robotics based on a generalization of Asimov's laws. The deployment of AI in physical robot bodies introduces failure modes that do not exist for software-only systems—physical harm, infrastructure damage, autonomous action in uncontrolled environments. As these models become available to any robotics company through the Gemini API, how does DeepMind maintain oversight of downstream physical deployments? Does the constitutional AI framework extend to third-party implementations, or does safety governance end at the API boundary?

---

### To Brett Adcock — Figure AI

**Q1.** Figure AI's valuation rose from $2.6 billion to $39 billion in eighteen months—a 15x increase—making it the most valuable pure-play humanoid robotics company. Figure 03 launched in October 2025, BotQ is operational, and you have paying customers in BMW and a second major U.S. company, with a stated path to 100,000 robots over four years. You exited your OpenAI partnership in February 2025 citing a "major breakthrough" in in-house AI and the need to vertically integrate. Given this trajectory, what is Figure's specific timeline for deployment at a scale that measurably displaces human workers in the sectors you're targeting? And what does Figure believe its responsibility is to the workers displaced by that deployment?

**Q2.** Your Helix AI system—a proprietary vision-language-action model with a dual System 1/System 2 architecture—represents a bet that embodied AI requires purpose-built intelligence, not general-purpose language models. You've stated that LLMs are "getting smarter yet more commoditized" and that "for us, LLMs have quickly become the smallest piece of the puzzle." If this is correct, it implies that the intelligence bottleneck for physical labor replacement has been broken. What are the remaining bottlenecks to mass deployment, and on what timeline does Figure expect them to be resolved?

**Q3.** The humanoid form factor is a deliberate choice—it means your robots can operate in environments built for human bodies, using tools designed for human hands, without requiring infrastructure modification. Figure 03 is specifically designed for home environments, with safety-focused soft materials, multi-density foam coverings, and removable washable textiles. This is not an industrial tool. It is a household replacement for human labor in the most intimate setting possible. How does Figure think about the social and psychological implications of deploying autonomous humanoid robots in people's homes, and what is the company's position on the economic displacement that home automation at scale would represent?

---

### To Mark Zuckerberg — Meta

**Q1.** In May 2025, Meta formally launched a dedicated robotics division within Reality Labs. CTO Andrew Bosworth's internal memo stated the goal is developing "consumer humanoid robots" powered by Llama. Meta is in discussions with Unitree Robotics and Figure AI for hardware partnerships. Meanwhile, Meta's open-source Llama models can already be paired with commercially available robot hardware—any developer can download Llama and use it to control a $5,900 Unitree R1. What is Meta's position on the tension between open-source AI development and the need for managed deployment timelines for physically embodied systems? Does Meta bear any responsibility for downstream robotic applications of its open-source models?

**Q2.** Meta's business model depends on mass consumer engagement and advertiser-funded revenue. Meta is now simultaneously spending $65 billion on AI infrastructure including robotics while depending on the consumer economy that embodied AI will disrupt. Has Meta modeled the point at which AI-driven economic disruption—particularly from physical automation powered in part by Llama—begins to undermine its own revenue base? What is Meta's long-term business model in a post-labor economy?

**Q3.** You have personally explored the concept of community-funded basic income through the Chan Zuckerberg Initiative. Meta is now directly investing in consumer humanoid robotics while its open-source models will power robotic systems built by other companies worldwide. Do you believe private philanthropy is sufficient to address the economic disruption this technology will cause, or is structural policy change necessary? If the latter, what specific policies does Meta support, and what lobbying resources are directed toward them?

---

### To Sam Altman — OpenAI

**Q1.** OpenAI invested in both Figure AI and 1X Technologies to extend its intelligence into physical robot bodies. Then Figure exited the partnership in February 2025, with CEO Brett Adcock stating that outsourcing AI to OpenAI was incompatible with solving embodied AI at scale. OpenAI has since rebuilt its robotics team, hired Caitlin Kalinowski from Meta to lead hardware efforts, and filed trademark applications referencing humanoid robots. Reports suggest OpenAI is developing its own robot hardware with custom sensors. What is OpenAI's current strategy for embodied AI? Is OpenAI building its own humanoid robot, and if so, what economic disruption modeling has OpenAI conducted for a future where its models—whether deployed through its own hardware or third-party platforms—control physical systems that replace human labor?

**Q2.** You have proposed "universal basic compute"—giving every person access to AI compute as a resource. In a world where robots perform physical labor, compute is not just a digital resource; it is the control layer for the physical economy. Whoever controls compute allocation controls what the robots do and for whom. How does "universal basic compute" interact with the embodied AI future? Is the vision that individuals would direct their compute allocation toward personal robotic services? And if so, who owns the physical robots?

**Q3.** OpenAI was founded as a nonprofit with the mission of ensuring AGI benefits all of humanity. Each corporate restructuring has moved the economic benefits further from public ownership. Meanwhile, OpenAI's investments in robotics companies are structured as standard venture investments with financial returns flowing to OpenAI's corporate entity, not to any public trust. Figure AI's valuation went from $2.6 billion to $39 billion in eighteen months—generating enormous returns for OpenAI as an early investor. How do you reconcile the progressive privatization of AGI's economic upside—now extending into physical automation through robotics investments—with the mission of universal benefit?

---

### To Dario Amodei — Anthropic

**Q1.** Your essay "Machines of Loving Grace" described a future in which AI dramatically accelerates progress in health, science, governance, and economic development. The essay acknowledged potential for disruption but was notably light on the physical automation dimension—the deployment of AI in robot bodies that perform manual labor. As embodied AI systems become commercially viable, does Anthropic's responsible scaling framework extend to any assessment of how Anthropic's models might be used in robotics applications? Does Anthropic track whether its API is being used to control physical systems?

**Q2.** Anthropic is a public benefit corporation. The embodied AI pipeline—where Anthropic's models could be integrated into robotic systems by third parties—creates a scenario where Anthropic's technology contributes to physical labor displacement without Anthropic directly deploying any robots. Does the PBC structure create any obligation regarding downstream use of Anthropic's models in physical automation? Or is the responsibility boundary drawn at the API?

**Q3.** You have argued that the risk of not developing AI is as great as the risk of developing it. But the embodiment of AI—its extension into physical robot systems—represents a qualitative escalation. Software AI displaces cognitive tasks but leaves physical production intact. Embodied AI displaces both. Has Anthropic considered that the deployment of AI in physical systems may warrant a different risk calculus than the deployment of software-only AI, and if so, does that affect Anthropic's approach to model access for robotics companies?

---

### To Jeff Bezos — Amazon, Blue Origin, Investor

**Q1.** You have invested personally in Figure AI, Physical Intelligence, and other robotics ventures. Amazon operates over 750,000 robots in its fulfillment network and acquired Covariant's AI team to build autonomous warehouse capabilities. Amazon is simultaneously one of the world's largest employers (over 1.5 million people) and one of the most aggressive deployers of automation designed to replace those same employees. What is Amazon's internal timeline for when its fulfillment operations become majority-automated? And what specific commitment has Amazon made to the workers who will be displaced by that transition?

**Q2.** Amazon's acquisition strategy—buying Covariant's AI team, deploying Agility's Digit robots, investing in autonomous delivery—suggests a comprehensive plan for end-to-end automation of its physical operations. Amazon also depends on mass consumer purchasing power for its revenue. At what point does Amazon's own automation strategy begin to undermine the consumer spending that drives its business? Has Amazon modeled this feedback loop?

**Q3.** Your personal investment portfolio spans the embodied AI pipeline: Figure (humanoid hardware), Physical Intelligence (robot foundation models), and Amazon (deployment at scale). You are positioned to profit at every layer of the stack that automates physical labor. Given this position, what is your view on public ownership stakes in companies that deploy automation at scale? Should the public have equity in the systems that will perform the labor previously performed by the public?

---

## VIII. The Question Beneath the Questions

Every question above converges on a single underlying tension. The leaders of frontier AI companies and the architects of the embodied AI pipeline describe a future of extraordinary abundance and human flourishing. They also describe a future that arrives on a timeline measured in years, not generations. The gap between those two claims—between the speed of the disruption and the speed at which human institutions can adapt—is the central problem of the next two decades.

The embodiment of AI makes this gap more dangerous, not less. When AI was confined to software, the disruption was economic but not physical. When AI inhabits robot bodies operating in factories, warehouses, farms, construction sites, and eventually homes and public spaces, the disruption is total. It touches every sector, every skill level, every geography.

The data from 2025 makes the trajectory unmistakable. Over 13,000 humanoid robots shipped globally. Google DeepMind went from launching Gemini Robotics to deploying agentic robot models that plan, search the internet, and explain their reasoning—in seven months. Tesla converted car production lines to robot production lines. Figure AI's valuation increased fifteenfold in eighteen months. Chinese companies shipped thirty-five times more humanoid units than Tesla. Manufacturing costs dropped 40% in a single year. Unitree launched a humanoid robot for $5,900. Meta opened a consumer robotics division. xAI merged with SpaceX to build an integrated intelligence-to-embodiment pipeline. And 1X Technologies opened consumer preorders for a home humanoid robot.

None of these developments were predicted five years ago. Most were not predicted two years ago. The pace of convergence between AI intelligence and physical robotics hardware has outrun every mainstream forecast.

The honest version of the situation is this: we know how to build the technology. We do not know how to manage the transition. The economic models are incomplete. The political will is uncertain. The institutional capacity is untested. And the people with the most knowledge, the most resources, and the most influence over the timeline are the same people whose financial incentives point toward moving as fast as possible.

This is not an argument against developing AI or embodied robotics. It is an argument for specificity. The era of "we'll figure it out" is over. The deployment is underway. The first humanoid robots are in warehouses and on factory floors. The foundation models for robot control are available via API. The investment capital is committed. The displacement is beginning. The time for detailed plans—not visions, not slogans, not philosophical musings, but plans with mechanisms and timelines and commitments—was yesterday.

The architects of this transition owe the rest of us more than optimism. They owe us answers.

---

*Julian is an entrepreneur based in Bend, Oregon, who writes about the intersection of AI development, economic systems, and the practical realities of technological transition. This article draws on analysis conducted in collaboration with multiple AI systems, which seems fitting given the subject matter.*
